p.s:
We can mark these on our graph; we can see that $@f@prime\left( @x \right)$ is increasing for the following values of $@x$:
 \begin{gather*} @x < 2,\\
 3 < @x < 5,\\
 @x > 7.  \end{gather*}

Similarly, we can see $@f@prime\left( @x \right)$ is decreasing for the following values of $@x$:
 \begin{gather*} 2 < @x < 3,\\
 5 <@x < 7.  \end{gather*}

By looking at our graph, we can see that


when $@x < 1$, $@f\left( @x \right)$ has a negative slope;

when $1 < @x < 5$, $@f\left( @x \right)$ has a positive slope.

Similarly,


when $1 < @x < 5$, $@f\left( @x \right)$ has a positive slope;

when $@x > 5$, $@f\left( @x \right)$ has a negative slope.
